Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 am, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of bed, he put on his combat uniform, wore his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, glasses, everything necessary. After checking his pockets for ammunition, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of mud and crushed ice resonating under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other side. As he lit it, he took a small puff before opening the door gently. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm clock; half the time it didn't work, as anything coming from the speakers was just a slight whistling.
"You're waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Yep," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first off, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up this morning. Second, the first shock troops awake get first dibs on breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and pressed a switch. A loud alarm sounded inside the barracks, echoing and shrill. He heard commotion and noise inside.
"For Christ's sake, Valturi," Nemic called out. "We might have thought they'd learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned toward Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, again, their platoon and section leaders know how to wake up before their units.
A few seconds later, the rest of the company poured out en masse. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more agitated.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren cheerfully.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop squad members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't sleep in," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As first lieutenant and second-in-command to the captain, it was his responsibility to oversee and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to perform final checks and gather supplies for the day."
The members of Company Exodus dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. This was a fragmented company, and Cohren wasn't sure how he felt about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly due to the reasons that motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the first platoon leader, walked together under the lights of the advanced operational base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both aerial and ground-based, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the hell pioneers," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," replied Cohren, pulling on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he kept quiet.
"Shit. The situation is worsening on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from here is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, throwing his butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're going with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Did Daybreak provide us with transportation?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable either."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of Company Exodus, assemble at the west vehicle park once you're done. We leave with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking sergeants when they arrived here. All four had been very good friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like it was so long ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon since last week, after the demobilization of the previous commander who was injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, ensuring that their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw turned around and walked towards them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at him again. "I suppose the company is ready."
